{"title_page": "Copenhagen Castle", "text_new": "{{expand Danish|K\u00f8benhavns Slot|date=June 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox Historic building\n|image     = Copenhagen Castle 1698.jpg\n|caption   = Copenhagen Castle painted in 1698 by unknown artist\n|name      = Copenhagen Castle\n|location_town = [[Copenhagen]]\n|location_country = [[Denmark]]\n|architect =  \n|client    =  \n|engineer  = \n|construction_start_date = Late 14th century\n|completion_date = \n|date_demolished = 1731 \n|cost      = \n|structural_system = \n|style     =\n}}\n'''Copenhagen Castle''' ({{lang-da|K\u00f8benhavns Slot}}) was a castle on [[Slotsholmen]] in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. It was built in the late 14th century at the site of the current [[Christiansborg Palace]].<ref name=\"Copenhagen\"/>\n\n[[File:K\u00f8benhavns Slot (Resen).png|thumb|250px|Copenhagen Castle seen on  illustration from [[Peder Hansen Resen]]'s Atlas Danica]] \n\n==History==\nIn 1167, Bishop  [[Absalon]] (c.\u20091128\u20131201) founded a fortress on the islet of [[Slotsholmen]] in the harbour of Copenhagen. It consisted of a courtyard with several buildings and surrounded by a wall for protection. During the years after the demolition of [[Absalon's Castle|Bishop Absalon's Castle]] by the [[Hansa League]] in 1369, the ruins on the island were covered with earthworks, on which the new stronghold, Copenhagen Castle, was built. In 1343 King [[Valdemar Atterdag]] took over Absalon's castle, but upon his death in 1375 the right to the property returned to the [[Diocese of Roskilde]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://denstoredanske.dk/Danmarks_geografi_og_historie/Danmarks_historie/Danmark_f%C3%B8r_Reformationen/Absalon |title= Absalon|website=  Den Store Danske, Gyldendal |author=  Kai H\u00f8rby |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Copenhagen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.visitcopenhagen.com/copenhagen/ruins-under-christiansborg-palace-gdk423233|title=Ruins under Christiansborg Palace|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=  https://www.thedanishparliament.dk/en/christiansborg-palace/the-history-of-christiansborg-palace|title=   Absalon's Castle|website= thedanishparliament.dk |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedanishparliament.dk/en/christiansborg-palace/the-history-of-christiansborg-palace   |title=   Copenhagen Castle|website= thedanishparliament.dk |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe castle had a curtain wall and was surrounded by a moat which had an inner diameter of about 50 meters  and with a large, solid tower as an entrance gate. The castle was still the property of the [[Bishop of Roskilde]] until King [[Eric of Pomerania]] usurped the rights to the castle in 1417. The [[Hanseatic League]] attacked the castle and  in the [[Bombardment of Copenhagen (1428)|Bombardment of Copenhagen]]  during the [[Dano-Hanseatic War (1426\u20131435)]]. The attack was fought back by in 1428 by [[Philippa of England|Queen Philippa]], who led the defense from Copenhagen Castle.  <ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.hcandersen-homepage.dk/?page_id=1325 |title=   Gudfaders Billedbog|website=hcandersen-homepage.dk  \n|author= Hans Christian Andersen|date=  1868   |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrom the middle of the 15th century, the castle served as the Danish monarch's main residence and center of government.\nThe castle was expanded and rebuilt several times. King [[Christian IV of Denmark|Christian IV]], added a spire to the large entrance tower, which under the name of the [[Bl\u00e5t\u00e5rn|Blue Tower]] gained a reputation as a prison. In the 1720s, King [[Frederick IV of Denmark|Frederik IV]] entirely rebuilt the castle, but it became so heavy that the walls began to give way and to crack. It became therefore evident to King [[Christian VI of Denmark|Christian VI]], Frederik IV's successor, immediately after his accession to the throne in 1730, that an entirely new castle had to be built. The demolition of the overextended and antiquated Copenhagen Castle was commenced in 1731 to make room for the [[Christiansborg Palace (1st)|first Christiansborg Palace]].<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://www.thedanishparliament.dk/en/christiansborg-palace     \n|title=   The History of Christiansborg |website= thedanishparliament.dk |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedanishparliament.dk/en/christiansborg-palace/the-history-of-christiansborg-palace|title= First Christiansborg Palace|website= thedanishparliament.dk |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{commons category| Copenhagen Castle}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==Other sources==\n*Frydendal, Flemming (red) (2005)  ''Ruinerne under Christiansborg'' (K\u00f8benhavn: Slots- og Ejendomsstyrelsen)  {{ISBN|87-990389-4-3}}\n*Hvidt, Kristian; Elleh\u00f8j, Svend; Norn, Otto (1975)  ''Christiansborg Slot I-II. Udgivet af Folketingets pr\u00e6sidium'' (K\u00f8benhavn: Nyt Nordisk Forlag Arnold Busck) {{ISBN|87-1701955-9}} \n{{coord|55|40|38|N|12|34|48|E|region:DK_type:landmark_source:kolossus-nowiki|display=title}}{{Castles in Denmark}}\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in the 14th century]]\n[[Category:Castles in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Former buildings and structures in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Destroyed landmarks in Denmark]]\n[[Category:History of Copenhagen]]\n", "text_old": "{{expand Danish|K\u00f8benhavns Slot|date=June 2012}}\n\n{{Infobox Historic building\n|image     = Copenhagen Castle 1698.jpg\n|caption   = Copenhagen Castle painted in 1698 by unknown artist\n|name      = Copenhagen Castle\n|location_town = [[Copenhagen]]\n|location_country = [[Denmark]]\n|architect =  \n|client    =  \n|engineer  = \n|construction_start_date = Late 14th century\n|completion_date = \n|date_demolished = 1731 \n|cost      = \n|structural_system = \n|style     =\n}}\n'''Copenhagen Castle''' ({{lang-da|K\u00f8benhavns Slot}}) was a castle on [[Slotsholmen]] in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. It was built in the late 14th century at the site of the current [[Christiansborg Palace]].<ref name=\"Copenhagen\"/>\n\n[[File:K\u00f8benhavns Slot (Resen).png|thumb|250px|Copenhagen Castle seen on  illustration from [[Peder Hansen Resen]]'s Atlas Danica]] \n\n==History==\nIn 1167, Bishop  [[Absalon]] (c.\u20091128\u20131201) founded a fortress on the islet of [[Slotsholmen]] in the harbour of Copenhagen. It consisted of a courtyard with several buildings and surrounded by a wall for protection. During the years after the demolition of [[Absalon's Castle|Bishop Absalon's Castle]] by the [[Hansa League]] in 1369, the ruins on the island were covered with earthworks, on which the new stronghold, Copenhagen Castle, was built. In 1343 King [[Valdemar Atterdag]] took over Absalon's castle, but upon his death in 1375 the right to the property returned to the [[Diocese of Roskilde]].<ref>{{cite web|url= http://denstoredanske.dk/Danmarks_geografi_og_historie/Danmarks_historie/Danmark_f%C3%B8r_Reformationen/Absalon |title= Absalon|website=  Den Store Danske, Gyldendal |author=  Kai H\u00f8rby |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Copenhagen\">{{cite web|url=http://www.visitcopenhagen.com/copenhagen/ruins-under-christiansborg-palace-gdk423233|title=Ruins under Christiansborg Palace|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=  https://www.thedanishparliament.dk/en/christiansborg-palace/the-history-of-christiansborg-palace|title=   Absalon's Castle|website= thedanishparliament.dk |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedanishparliament.dk/en/christiansborg-palace/the-history-of-christiansborg-palace   |title=   Copenhagen Castle|website= thedanishparliament.dk |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe castle had a curtain wall and was surrounded by a moat which had an inner diameter of about 50 meters  and with a large, solid tower as an entrance gate. The castle was still the property of the [[Bishop of Roskilde]] until King [[Eric of Pomerania]] usurped the rights to the castle in 1417. The [[Hanseatic League]] attacked the castle and  in the [[Bombardment of Copenhagen (1428)|Bombardment of Copenhagen]]  during the [[Dano-Hanseatic War (1426\u20131435)]]. The attack was fought back by in 1428 by [[Philippa of England|Queen Philippa]], who led the defense from Copenhagen Castle.  <ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.hcandersen-homepage.dk/?page_id=1325 |title=   Gudfaders Billedbog|website=hcandersen-homepage.dk  \n|author= Hans Christian Andersen|date=  1868   |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrom the middle of the 15th century, the castle served as the Danish residence's main residence and center of government.\nThe castle was expanded and rebuilt several times. King [[Christian IV of Denmark|Christian IV]], added a spire to the large entrance tower, which under the name of the [[Bl\u00e5t\u00e5rn|Blue Tower]] gained a reputation as a prison. In the 1720s, King [[Frederick IV of Denmark|Frederik IV]] entirely rebuilt the castle, but it became so heavy that the walls began to give way and to crack. It became therefore evident to King [[Christian VI of Denmark|Christian VI]], Frederik IV's successor, immediately after his accession to the throne in 1730, that an entirely new castle had to be built. The demolition of the overextended and antiquated Copenhagen Castle was commenced in 1731 to make room for the [[Christiansborg Palace (1st)|first Christiansborg Palace]].<ref>{{cite web|url=  https://www.thedanishparliament.dk/en/christiansborg-palace     \n|title=   The History of Christiansborg |website= thedanishparliament.dk |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thedanishparliament.dk/en/christiansborg-palace/the-history-of-christiansborg-palace|title= First Christiansborg Palace|website= thedanishparliament.dk |access-date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{{commons category| Copenhagen Castle}}\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n==Other sources==\n*Frydendal, Flemming (red) (2005)  ''Ruinerne under Christiansborg'' (K\u00f8benhavn: Slots- og Ejendomsstyrelsen)  {{ISBN|87-990389-4-3}}\n*Hvidt, Kristian; Elleh\u00f8j, Svend; Norn, Otto (1975)  ''Christiansborg Slot I-II. Udgivet af Folketingets pr\u00e6sidium'' (K\u00f8benhavn: Nyt Nordisk Forlag Arnold Busck) {{ISBN|87-1701955-9}} \n{{coord|55|40|38|N|12|34|48|E|region:DK_type:landmark_source:kolossus-nowiki|display=title}}{{Castles in Denmark}}\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in the 14th century]]\n[[Category:Castles in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Former buildings and structures in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Destroyed landmarks in Denmark]]\n[[Category:History of Copenhagen]]\n", "name_user": "JCO312", "label": "safe", "comment": "correcting sentence to fix \u201cresidence\u2019s residence\u201d", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Copenhagen_Castle"}
